[4] Brazil and eye lesions
Date: Thu 7 Jan 2016
Source: The Lancet on line DOI: http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00006-4 [edited]
http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(16)00006-4/fulltext

Camila V Ventura, Mauricio Maia, Vasco Bravo-Filho, Adriana L Gois, Rubens Belfort Jr. Zika virus in Brazil and macular atrophy in a child with microcephaly.

Here we report ophthalmic findings in 3 children with microcephaly born after the ZIKV outbreak in Brazil. These infants had cerebral calcifications detected by CT scans and presumable intrauterus ZIKV infection. 1 of the mothers reported rash and arthralgia in the 1st trimester. Toxoplasmosis, rubella, cytomegalovirus, herpes simplex, syphillis, and HIV were ruled out in all cases (mothers and infants), fulfilling the Ministry of Health's criteria for ZIKV vertical infection.

Mothers and infants underwent ocular examination that included biomicroscopy and fundus examination. The mothers had no ocular lesions. The 3 infants had unilateral ocular findings involving solely the macular region. All 3 infants presented with gross macular pigment mottling and foveal reflex loss. A well-defined macular neuroretinal atrophy was detected in one child.

To our knowledge, this is the 1st report of ocular findings in infants with microcephaly born after the ZIKV outbreak. All 3 children had fundoscopic alterations in the macular region. Although ZIKV infection was not tested by real-time PCR, cases fulfill criteria for ZIKV vertical infection. Further studies are being conducted in a larger group of infants to assess the ocular manifestations of ZIKV vertical infection.

--
Communicated by
David M. Morens, M.D.
<dm270q@nih.gov>

[Evidence for fetal infection by Zika virus continues to mount. Although these cases did meet the Brazil Ministry of Health criteria for Zika virus vertical infection, in fatal cases in the future it would be of interest to test eye and other tissues for presence of the virus. - Mod.TY]

******
Date: Sat 9 Jan 2016
Source: El Universal [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.eluniversal.com/nacional-y-politica/160109/alertan-brote-de-virus-similar-al-zika-en-maracaibo

An alert has been issued for an outbreak of a virus similar to Zika in Maracaibo
--------
The Director of the Maracaibo University Hospital [SAHUM], Samuel Viloria, announced that a safety protocol due to an outbreak of a virus similar to Zika. [He said] "we are dealing with Guillain-Barre disease [GBS], an acute inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy of unknown origin."

He said that the pathophysiology is not completely clear, and stated that an infectious agent induces an immunological response that is both humoral and cellular, that produces a cross reaction against the myelin sheath of peripheral nerves that causes their destruction.

The virus [GBS?] is presenting with much frequency and is preceded by a virus infection followed by a clinical picture with neurological sequellae that includes muscular paralysis that can affect respiratory muscles.

"There have been 7 patients admitted in critical condition by the Adult Emergency Services of SAHUM, but we now, have an additional 4 people registered in recuperation wards who have downgraded from the critical phase," the Director of the Maracaibo Hospital stated.

It is recommended that homes be fumigated to eliminate mosquito breeding sites now that GBS initially presents with symptoms of Zika virus [infection].

[Byline: Teresa Luengo]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This report does not provide information linking the GBS cases to Zika virus infections. There is no indication that the GBS patients have been shown to have been infected by the virus. Because GBS has been reported to occur in a small proportion of individuals who have been infected with the virus, if there really are 7 post-Zika GBS cases, that implies that there must be hundreds of individuals in Maracaibo who have had Zika virus infections. To date, no such reports of large numbers of cases have come to ProMED, and ProMED would be very interested in receiving them.

[A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Venezuela can be accessed at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3925377,29. - Mod.TY]
